results.title: Derek Chauvin Found Guilty in Death of George Floyd

-MYkmWmLhVGGMbecFVti.text: A verdict has been reached in the trial of former Minneapolis Police officer Derek Chauvin, who has been charged in the death of George Floyd.

-MYlCAYXkZmqmHGbdfWs.text: Police have reported several large crowds gathered outside Hennepin County Courthouse.

nib.text:
Former Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin has been convicted of murder and manslaughter in George Floyd’s death. 

The jury deliberated for approximately 11 hours before announcing their unanimous decision in Hennepin County Court on Tuesday afternoon.

After the jury's verdict was announced, Judge Peter Cahill revoked bail and ordered Chauvin to be remanded into police custody. 
 
Chauvin was found guilty on all three charges: second-degree murder, third-degree murder, and second-degree manslaughter. The most serious charge carries a maximum sentence of 40 years in prison.

Chauvin, 45, was filmed kneeling on Floyd's neck for more than nine minutes on May 25, 2020, while Floyd, 46, told him he could not breathe dozens of times. Floyd was arrested after being accused of trying to pass a counterfeit $20 bill at a Minneapolis convenience store. He died in police custody.

Video of Floyd's death circulated online and ignited protests against police brutality and racial injustice worldwide. 

The three other officers at the scene were fired. Thomas Lane, Alexander Kueng, and Tou Thao are charged with aiding and abetting murder and scheduled to go on trial in August.

nib.text:
Fire tore through a church in northeast Minneapolis Monday evening. 

Minneapolis firefighters responded to the blaze in a two-story church on the 2200 block of 5th Street NE just before 7 p.m. 

When units arrived, they found heavy fire in the rear of the building and in the attic space. 

Officials requested a second-alarm assignment to bring additional personnel and equipment to the scene. 

Citizen users shared video of firefighters using aerial ladders while they worked to contain the blaze.

Fire officials said there was heavy fire throughout the church, the roof, and in the bell tower. The majority of the roof collapsed.

According to the MFD, no one was inside the church.

The cause of the fire is under investigation.
